    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-09-21T16:49:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-09-21T16:49:00-05:00" n="99"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                <head>99. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission to the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d99fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 3–1. Confidential.
                        Drafted by Schrage; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_AJA1"
                            >Armitage</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OCPT1">O’Connor</persName>,
                        and Kerrigan; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_HMF1"
                        >Herz</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-09-21T21:49:00+00:00">September 21, 1971,
                        2149Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>173644. Subject: Pruning of 26th <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> Agenda. Ref:
                        <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> 2769.<note n="2" xml:id="d99fn2"
                        >Telegram 2769 from <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, September 14,
                        discussed items that the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> and Soviet
                        delegations had proposed postponing or deleting from the agenda of the 26th
                        General Assembly. (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_DEPT1">Dept</gloss> supports retention of agenda items 54
                        (freedom of information) and 64 (High Commissioner for Human Rights) but can
                        agree to postpone item 90 (international school) per Soviet suggestion
                            <gloss target="#t_REFTEL1">reftel</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>After further consideration of item 55 (elderly and aged), <gloss
                            target="#t_DEPT1">Dept</gloss> has decided that while we could support
                        postponement and referral of this item to <gloss target="#t_ECOSOC1"
                            >ECOSOC</gloss> and its Social Commission, we do not wish to propose
                        this ourselves. <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>: There will be a White
                        House Conference on elderly and aged in November 1971. While we see no
                        positive advantage for this conference in keeping item 55 on agenda, believe
                        it would be inopportune for us to propose postponement at this time. End
                            <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
